## Essay title

**Compare and contrast the Raven’s Matrices and Weschler Adult Intelligence Scale. Which is the better measure in your view and why?**

## Summary of a strong essay

Strong essays should clearly explain general intelligence (g) and Cattell’s distinction between fluid (Gf) and crystallised (Gc) intelligence), then use these ideas to compare the Wechsler Adult Intelligence Scale (WAIS) and Raven’s Progressive Matrices (RM). The WAIS measures both Gf and Gc through 12 subtests, producing Verbal, Performance, and Full-Scale IQ scores; it is comprehensive, statistically reliable, and highly predictive of academic and occupational outcomes, but culturally biased, time-consuming, and dependent on education and language. Raven’s Matrices measure only Gf via abstract, non-verbal pattern reasoning, offering a quicker and more "culture-fair" test used in heritability and cross-cultural research, but with narrower scope and weaker predictive validity. Good essays justify which is "better" — perhaps arguing WAIS for diagnostic breadth and predictive power, RM for fairness and focus on innate reasoning — or might argue that suitability depends on context.
Markers should look for clear conceptual grounding in g, Gf, and Gc; accurate description of each test; and critical evaluation supported by evidence (e.g., adoption/SES studies showing Gc’s environmental influence, twin studies linking Gf to heritability, high WAIS–WASI correlations, cultural bias data, and age effects on Gf vs Gc). Strong essays integrate such evidence to explain why one test is preferable or more appropriate for a given purpose, not just state it.
Higher-quality answers connect theory to application, discuss cultural and social implications (fairness, labelling, equity), and show awareness that intelligence testing is both scientifically useful and socially constructed. Essays may differ in conclusion, but reward should go to coherent argumentation, conceptual precision, and critical engagement rather than rote description.
Essays were written under exam conditions, so memorisation of citations or specific studies is less important than good explanations of key ideas and linking these to an clear answer to the question.

